    Research Reports: QQQ

    • Good Year for Global Stocks

      We have three strategic asset-allocation models based on risk-tolerance: Conservative, Growth, and Aggressive. We make tactical adjustments to the models, based on our outlooks for the various segments of the capital markets. In terms of performance year to date, stocks and bonds are close, with stocks pulling a few hundred basis points ahead through August. From an asset-allocation standpoint, our model still slightly favors bonds over stocks for long-term portfolio positioning. We are over-weight on large-caps at this stage of the market cycle. We favor them for growth exposure and financial strength, as well as exposure to the IT sector. Our recommended exposure to small- and mid-caps is 5%-10% of equity allocation, below the benchmark weighting. The dearth of IPOs has meant a lack of exciting new companies in the marketplace. While the top tier of stocks (the Mag 7) soared on enthusiasm for AI, legacy small companies haven't been able to innovate to the same degree. One of the surprises this year has been the performance of global stocks, with an impressive performance lead in 2025. We expect the long-term trend favoring U.S. stocks to re-emerge, given volatile global economic, political, geopolitical, and currency conditions. That said, international stocks offer favorable near-term valuations and we target 15%-20% of equity exposure to the group. In terms of growth and value, growth rebounded in 2023-2024 and outperformed value as interest rates stabilized and started lower, though value was off to a good start in 2025. Key value sectors that may be less exposed to global trade wars include Consumer Staples, Healthcare, Utilities, and Financial (via regional banks).

      Argus• 2 days ago
       

    • Argus Quick Note: Weekly Stock List for 09/08/2025: Companies Raising Guidance

      During the recent earnings season, many companies across many sectors raised guidance. That is admirable, especially during uncertain economic times. We track the companies raising guidance and look for trends. Indeed, Management Signals is one of our Investment Themes for 2025. The sectors with the most companies raising guidance in the past quarter were Communication Services, Healthcare, Industrial, and Information Technology. Sectors underrepresented were Financial, Energy, and Consumer Staples. Raising guidance in the face of tariff and macroeconomic uncertainty could signal strong management, flexibility, and resilience. As well, increased guidance is often a catalyst for market-beating returns in the quarters ahead. The following is a partial list of companies in Argus' Fundamental Universe of Coverage at which management increased its outlook during the recent reporting season, with our rating and the sector designation noted. We like this theme, as it crosses numerous industries and generates a robust list of potential portfolio candidates.

      Argus• 3 days ago
       

    • Alphabet: Remedies Proposed in the Google Search Case Do Not Pose a Material Risk to Alphabet

      Alphabet is a holding company that wholly owns internet giant Google. The California-based company derives slightly less than 90% of its revenue from Google services, the vast majority of which is advertising sales. Alongside online ads, Google services houses sales stemming from Google’s subscription services (YouTube TV, YouTube Music among others), platforms (sales and in-app purchases on Play Store), and devices (Chromebooks, Pixel smartphones, and smart home products such as Chromecast). Google’s cloud computing platform, or GCP, accounts for roughly 10% of Alphabet’s revenue with the firm’s investments in up-and-coming technologies such as self-driving cars (Waymo), health (Verily), and internet access (Google Fiber) making up the rest.
